A quick refresh on our last session

What is an ERD?

Definition

An Entity-Relationship Diagram (ERD) visually represents the data and relationships in a system.

Why use ERDs?

  • Clarify system requirements before building the database
  • Make sure all data is recorded correctly
  • Share the design in a clear way with developers and analysts

ERD Components

Main Components

  • Entities → Objects (Employee, Project)
  • Attributes → Properties (Name, StartDate)
  • Relationships → Connections (Works On)

Visual Elements

  • Rectangle → Entity
  • Oval → Attribute
  • Diamond → Relationship
Entity Attribute Relation

Entities

Entity: is a distinct and identifiable object in the real world or business domain about which data needs to be stored in a database

Types of Entities

Strong Entity

Can exist independently

Examples: Employee, Product

Weak Entity

Depends on another entity

Examples: Invoice Item depends on Invoice

💡 Remember: Each entity will become a table in the database.

Attributes

Attribute: is a property or piece of information that describes an entity or a relationship. it's represents a single type of data that we store about an entity (or sometimes about a relationship)

Types of Attributes

  • Simple: Single-valued (ProductName, Price)
  • Composite: Can be divided (Address → Street, City, ZipCode)
  • Multivalued: Many values (Skills, Languages)
  • Complex: Composite + Multivalued (Dependents → (Name, BirthDate) for multiple)
  • Derived: Calculated (TotalPrice from Quantity × UnitPrice)

Simple Attribute

➡️ ProductName and Price cannot be meaningfully broken into smaller parts — each represents one simple value.

Composite Attribute

➡️ Address and FullName attribute can be split into multiple simple attributes.

Multivalued Attribute

➡️ One customer can have many phones — so Phone is multivalued.

Complex Attribute

➡️ Address is multivalued (many addresses) AND each address has multiple components (street, city, zipcode).

Derived Attribute

➡️ Age is Derived can changes every year, better to calculate from BirthDate.

✅ Notes:

  • Used for attributes that change frequently or can be recomputed.
  • Reduces redundancy but may increase computation time.
  • Decision: Store vs Calculate depends on performance needs.
  • Example: Age changes every year, better to calculate from BirthDate.

🔑 Identifiers / Keys

Keys uniquely identify records.

Primary Key (PK)

Unique identifier (EmployeeID)

Candidate Key

Possible unique keys (Email, PassportNumber)

Alternate Key

Candidate keys not chosen as PK

Composite Key

Multiple fields (FlightNumber + Date)

Foreign Key (FK)

Links entities (DepartmentID in Employee)

Super Key

Any unique combination (EmployeeID + Name)

Rule: Every entity must have a unique identifier.

Relationship Types

Relationships describe how entities are connected in an ERD. They can involve one, two, or more entity types.

Unary (Recursive)

A relationship between instances of the same entity.

  • Also called self-relationship.
  • Example: An Employee supervises another Employee.

Binary

A relationship between two different entities.

  • Most common type in ERDs.
  • Example: Customer places an Order.

Ternary

A relationship involving three different entities.

  • Used when a single relationship depends on three entities together.
  • Example: Doctor prescribes a Medicine to a Patient.

Tip: The type of relationship depends on how many entity sets participate in it.

Cardinality

Cardinality defines the number of instances of one entity that can or must be associated with instances of another entity.

  • 1:1 (One-to-One) — Each entity in A is related to only one in B.
    Example: Each Person has one Passport.
  • 1:M (One-to-Many) — One record in A can relate to many in B.
    Example: One Department has many Employees.
  • M:N (Many-to-Many) — Many records in A can relate to many in B.
    Example: A Student can enroll in many Courses, and each course has many students.

Rule: Cardinality defines how many entities are related.

Participation

Participation shows whether all or only some entity instances are involved in a relationship.

  • Total Participation — Every instance must participate in the relationship.
    Example: Every Invoice must belong to a Customer.
  • Partial Participation — Some instances may or may not participate.
    Example: Not every Employee is assigned to a Project.

💡 Important: Participation defines whether entities must take part in the relationship.

Identifying vs. Non-Identifying

Identifying Relationship

Child depends on parent (Weak entity).

Example: Invoice → InvoiceItem

Non-Identifying

Child exists independently.

Example: Department → Employee

Weak Entities (Deep Dive)

  • Depend on another entity for identity
  • Cannot exist without parent entity
  • Represented by double rectangle and double diamond
  • Partial key: identifies within relationship

Example: Invoice → InvoiceItem

InvoiceItem has composite key (InvoiceID + ItemNumber)

Specialization (Top-Down)

Defines subclasses based on characteristics

"Employee can be Manager or Developer"

Parent: Employee

Sub-entities: Manager, Developer

Key Characteristics

  • Superclass: The general entity (e.g., Employee).
  • Subclass: The specialized entity (e.g., Manager, Developer).
  • Attribute Inheritance: Subclasses inherit all attributes of the superclass and may have additional ones.

Types:

  • Disjoint (D): An entity instance can belong to only one subclass.
    Example: An employee cannot be both a manager and a developer.
  • Overlapping (O): An entity instance can belong to multiple subclasses.
    Example: An employee can be both a trainer and a developer.

Generalization (Bottom-Up)

Combine similar entities into general entity

Example: Car, Truck → Vehicle

Key Characteristics

  • Bottom-Up Process: Starts by finding common features among entities.
  • Superclass: The newly created, more general entity (e.g., Vehicle).
  • Shared Attributes: Common properties are moved to the superclass.
  • Unique Attributes: Remain in the original sub-entities if still needed.

Purpose:

  • Reduce redundancy
  • Simplify relationships

Aggregation (Has-A)

Relationship participates in another relationship

Key Characteristics

  • Shows a “Has–A” or “Part–Of” relationship between a relationship and an entity.
  • Used when a relationship itself needs to participate in another relationship.
  • Represents a higher-level abstraction — treating the relationship as an entity.

Example: "Project employs Employees and uses Equipment"

Notation:

Diamond inside rectangle

💡: Relationship treated as entity.

ERD Best Practices

✅ Checklist

  • ✓ Use meaningful names
  • ✓ Avoid M:N without bridge entities
  • ✓ Keep attributes atomic
  • ✓ Every entity has primary key
  • ✓ Use consistent naming
  • ✓ Document assumptions

ERD → Relational Mapping

We now move from conceptual (ERD) to logical (relational) design

📘 Session Agenda

  • 🗄️ Relational Database Definitions
  • ⚙️ Mapping Rules
  • ✅ Session Activity
  • 🧩 Mini Exercise

🗄️ Relational Database Definitions

Key concepts and definitions for relational databases:

Database : An organized collection of structured data, consisting of various database objects such as tables, views, stored procedures, and triggers

Entity/Table : A collection of related data organized into rows and columns

Attribute / Column / Field : A specific piece of data stored in a table, representing a characteristic or property of the entity that the table describes

Row / Record / Tuple : A single entry in a table representing a unique instance of an entity

Normalization : The process of organizing data to reduce redundancy and improve integrity

⚙️ Mapping Rules — Simple Entities & Attributes

We now move from conceptual (ERD) to logical (relational) design. Each entity and attribute in the ERD must be accurately reflected in the schema.

  • Entity → Table — each entity becomes a table in the database.

Attribute Types

Different types of attributes require special handling when moving from ERD to tables.

  • Simple Attributes: Directly become columns.
  • Composite Attributes: Split into multiple columns.
  • Derived Attributes: Not stored, but calculated when needed.
    Example 💡: Age can be derived from BirthDate, so no need to store both.
  • Multivalued Attributes: Represented using a separate related table.
  • Complex Attributes: Contain a combination of composite and multivalued attributes (e.g., Address with multiple components and possible multiple entries).

Tip 💡: Always simplify — store only what’s necessary and derivable.

Key Design Decisions

Defining how records are identified and how data integrity is enforced is critical.

  • Primary Key (PK): Makes every record unique in a table.
  • Surrogate Key: System-generated ID (like auto-increment).
  • Natural Key: Based on existing real-world data (e.g., NationalID, Email).
  • Uniqueness: Some attributes must not repeat (e.g., usernames, emails).

Decision point 💭: Use surrogate keys when natural data might change or duplicate.

Mapping Relationships — Overview

After mapping entities and attributes, the next step is to represent relationships between tables. Each relationship type determines how entities connect and where foreign keys are placed.

  • One-to-One (1:1): Each instance in one table matches exactly one in another.
  • One-to-Many (1:M): Most common — child table holds a reference to the parent.
  • Many-to-Many (N:M): Requires a separate linking (associative) table.

Tip 💡: Understanding where the foreign key belongs is the key to correct mapping.

One-to-One (1:1) Relationships - Mandatory 1-1

Each record in one table is related to exactly one record in another.

  • Mapping Rule: One table contains a foreign key that also has a unique constraint.
  • Alternative: Merge both entities into a single table if it makes logical sense.

Each employee has exactly one car , Each car is assigned to exactly one specific employee.

A Mandatory 1-1 Relationship Between Employee and Car

Or

One-to-One (1:1) Relationships -Optional - Mandatory 1-1



Each employee may has one car , Each car is assigned to exactly one specific employee.

An Optional - Mandatory 1-1 Relationship Between Employee and Car

One-to-One (1:1) Relationships - Optional 1-1



Each employee may has one car , Each car may assigned to exactly one specific employee.

An Optional 1-1 Relationship Between Employee and Car

One-to-Many (1:M) Relationships

This is the most common relationship type in data models.

  • Definition: One entity instance in the parent is related to many in the child.
  • Mapping Rule: Place the foreign key in the child table.
  • Optional Participation: FK can be nullable (relationship not always required).
  • Mandatory Participation: FK must be not null (each child must have a parent).
Example 💡: A Customer can have many Accounts. The Account table holds the Customer reference.

One-to-Many — When “M” Is Optional

In this case, the child entity may or may not be linked to a parent entity.

  • Meaning: Some child records exist independently without a parent.
  • Mapping Effect: The foreign key can be empty (nullable).
  • Use Case: A Book might not yet be linked to a Publisher.

One-to-Many — When “M” Is Mandatory

Here, every child entity must be connected to an existing parent entity.

  • Meaning: The parent’s existence is required for any child record to exist.
  • Mapping Effect: The foreign key in the child table cannot be empty (not nullable).
  • Use Case: Every Order must belong to a Customer.

Many-to-Many (N:M) Relationships

When multiple instances of one entity are related to multiple instances of another, a new structure is required.

  • Definition: Many instances in both entities relate to each other.
  • Mapping Rule: Create a junction (associative) table containing FKs from both entities.
  • Composite Key: Both foreign keys together form a unique identifier.
  • Additional Attributes: Sometimes, the junction table includes extra data (e.g., DateAdded, Role).

Example 💡: A Customer can subscribe to many Services, and a Service can serve many Customers.

Optional vs Mandatory Participation

Participation defines whether a record must be linked to another entity.

  • Optional: Relationship may or may not exist — FK can be left empty.
  • Mandatory: Relationship must exist — FK cannot be null.
  • Design Impact: Affects data integrity and how constraints are applied.

Remember 💡: Participation rules from the ERD directly control nullability in the relational design.

Weak Entities

A weak entity depends on another (owner) entity for its identification.

  • Definition: Cannot exist without its owner — identified by a combination of its own partial key and the owner's key.
  • Mapping: The weak entity’s PK includes the owner’s FK.
  • Example: OrderItem depends on Order — each item is identified by (OrderId, ItemId).

Recursive Relationships

Sometimes, an entity relates to itself — e.g., an employee manages another employee.

  • Definition: A relationship where both roles are from the same entity set.
  • Mapping: Use a FK that references the same table’s PK.
  • Cardinality: Can be 1:1 or 1:N depending on the relationship design.
  • Example: Manager → Employee.

💡 Design Tip: Always label roles clearly (e.g., ManagerID, SupervisorID) to avoid confusion in recursive FKs.

Ternary Relationships

A ternary relationship occurs when an association involves exactly three entities at the same time

  • Definition: A relationship where both roles are from the same entity set.
  • Mapping: Create a table with foreign keys referencing the primary keys of all three entities.
  • Example: Vendor → Warehouse → Product (a Vendor Supplies Product From a specific Warehouse).

Advanced Constructs & Normalization Checks

Building a clean and maintainable database design through structured attribute handling and normalization principles.

  • Normalization:
    • 1NF: No repeating groups or multivalued attributes.
    • 2NF: Every non-key attribute fully depends on the whole primary key.
    • 3NF: No indirect dependencies between non-key attributes.
  • When to Denormalize: For performance in read-heavy systems — caching or reporting tables where redundancy is acceptable.
  • Audit Columns: Track changes using fields like CreatedDate, CreatedBy, ModifiedDate, ModifiedBy.
  • Soft Delete: Use a flag (e.g., IsDeleted) instead of physically removing data.
  • Concurrency Control: Use RowVersion or Timestamp columns to detect update conflicts.

💡 Tip: Normalize for data integrity — denormalize only for performance and reporting efficiency.

Normalization — First Normal Form (1NF)

Ensures that all attributes contain only indivisible (atomic) values.

  • Rule: Each column must hold a single value — no lists or repeating groups.
  • Goal: Eliminate multivalued attributes.

Before:

Student table — PhoneNumbers = "011111, 022222"

After:

Move phone numbers to a separate table: StudentPhone(StudentId, PhoneNumber)

💡 Reminder: Each cell = one value, one meaning.

Normalization — Second Normal Form (2NF)

Removes partial dependency — all non-key attributes must depend on the entire primary key.

  • Applies To: Tables with composite primary keys.
  • Goal: Ensure every attribute depends on the full key, not part of it.

Before:

CourseEnrollment(StudentId, CourseId, StudentName, Grade)

➜ StudentName depends only on StudentId

After:

Split into:

Student(StudentId, StudentName)

Enrollment(StudentId, CourseId, Grade)

💡 Tip: If part of a composite key determines a column — that’s a partial dependency.

Normalization — Third Normal Form (3NF)

Eliminates Indirect dependencies — non-key attributes must depend only on the key.

  • Rule: If A → B and B → C, then A → C should not exist in the same table.
  • Goal: Keep attributes dependent directly on the primary key.

Before:

Employee(EmpId, DeptId, DeptName)

➜ DeptName depends on DeptId, not EmpId.

After:

Split into:

Employee(EmpId, DeptId)

Department(DeptId, DeptName)

💡 Tip: Every non-key column must describe the key — nothing else.

When to Denormalize

Denormalization is the intentional introduction of redundancy to improve performance or simplify queries.

  • Reasons:
    • Frequent joins slow down reporting or analytics.
    • Need for summary or pre-aggregated data.
    • Improving read performance in large-scale systems.
  • Tradeoff: Speed vs Data Consistency.

Example:

Store TotalOrderAmount in Customer for quick reporting instead of recalculating from Orders every time.

💡 Tip: Denormalize only for performance — not convenience.

Audit Columns

Audit columns capture who made changes and when, enabling traceability and accountability.

  • Common Columns: CreatedBy, CreatedDate, ModifiedBy, ModifiedDate
  • Purpose: Track data lifecycle
  • Implementation: Often handled automatically via triggers or EF Core interceptors.

Example:

Employee(Id, Name, CreatedBy, CreatedDate, ModifiedBy, ModifiedDate)

💡 Best Practice: Always record who changed what and when.

Soft Delete

Instead of permanently removing data, a soft delete marks records as inactive or deleted for recovery or auditing.

  • Approach: Add a flag like IsDeleted (boolean).
  • Advantage: Data can be restored and referenced historically.
  • Consideration: Filters must exclude deleted data by default.

Example:

Customer(Id, Name, IsDeleted) — IsDeleted = 1 means archived but not removed.

💡 Tip: Always include a global query filter to hide deleted records automatically.

Concurrency Columns

Used to catch conflicts when two users try to update the same record at the same time.

  • Approach: Add a versioning column like RowVersion or Timestamp.
  • How it Works: The system checks if the version has changed before applying updates.
  • Goal: Prevent overwriting changes made by others.

Example:

Product(Id, Name, Price, RowVersion)

If RowVersion differs at update, a concurrency conflict is raised.

💡 Tip: Essential in collaborative environments or APIs with high parallel updates.
